00:48.040 --> 00:51.483
<i>The philosopher  Marcel Proust said,</i>

00:52.017 --> 00:54.985
<i> "We say that the hour of
 death cannot be forecast.</i>

00:56.253 --> 01:00.822
<i> But when we say this, we
 imagine that hour to be placed</i>

01:00.824 --> 01:03.658
<i> in an obscure and
 distant future."</i>

01:06.928 --> 01:09.029
<i>We gather here to offer support</i>

01:09.031 --> 01:10.930
<i> to Matthew's family
 and friends.</i>

01:12.198 --> 01:15.433
I must ask now, if your
cell phone is still on,

01:15.435 --> 01:17.601
please turn it off now
to be fully present.

01:24.741 --> 01:26.408
<i> There is never
 a convenient time</i>

01:26.410 --> 01:27.742
<i> for any of us to die.</i>

01:30.045 --> 01:32.780
<i> And yet, how do we
 make sense of such</i>

01:32.782 --> 01:35.415
<i> a promising young man's
 life cut so short?</i>

01:44.589 --> 01:46.590
<i> The eventual
 certainty for us all,</i>

01:47.758 --> 01:49.024
the hour of our death,

01:51.527 --> 01:52.793
suddenly went

01:53.127 --> 01:57.796
from obscure and distant
to a very unreal, reality.

02:00.099 --> 02:02.567
Yet, we are also
here to celebrate

02:02.569 --> 02:03.834
Matthew Burd's life,

02:05.269 --> 02:07.436
and in doing so,
knowing Matthew,

02:08.937 --> 02:12.040
he would want each of you
to live life as he did.

02:13.375 --> 02:14.641
To its fullest.

02:16.744 --> 02:18.511
That if opportunity
presents itself,

02:19.880 --> 02:22.314
do not hesitate, do not waver.

02:23.482 --> 02:25.382
Do not take time for granted.

02:26.884 --> 02:27.984
There is only now.

02:31.822 --> 02:33.087
Holy shit!

02:35.824 --> 02:37.124
Bye, see you later.

02:37.758 --> 02:39.959
You can stay as long as
you like, I'm going to Marie's.

02:40.660 --> 02:42.494
